Press Release
April 24th, 2006

For more information, contact:
David Prosser, SPARC,=20
<mailto:david.prosser@bodley.ox.ac.uk>david.prosser@bodley.ox.ac.uk

THE WELLCOME TRUST RECIEVES FIRST SPARC EUROPE=20
AWARD FOR OUTSTANDING ACHIEVEMENTS IN SCHOLARLY COMMUNICATIONS


Lund, Sweden =96 As part of the Third Nordic=20
Conference on Scholarly Communication: Beyond=20
Declarations - The Changing Landscape of=20
Scholarly Communication held in Lund, Sweden, the=20
Wellcome Trust was presented with the first SPARC=20
Europe Award for Outstanding Achievements in Scholarly Communications.

SPARC (the Scholarly Publishing and Academic=20
Resources Coalition) Europe initiated the Award=20
to recognise the work of an individual or group=20
within Europe that has made significant advances=20
in our understanding of the issues surrounding=20
scholarly communications and/or in developing=20
practical means to address the problems with the=20
current systems.  In making the Award to the=20
Trust the judging panel noted the Trust=92s truly=20
groundbreaking work in scholarly communication,=20
from the commissioning of incisive research into=20
the market, through to the formulation and=20
implementation of clear policy in support of the=20
widest dissemination of the research outputs funded by the Trust.

Dr Mark Walport, Director of the Wellcome Trust=20
said =91We are very honoured to receive this award=20
from SPARC Europe which recognises our activities=20
in the promotion of the =91open-access=92 model of=20
science publishing.  Ensuring that the outputs of=20
research are freely available and shared as=20
widely and as rapidly as possible is vital in=20
order to facilitate the translation of research=20
into practical improvements in health.=92

Dr Bas Savenije, Chair of the SPARC Europe Board,=20
praised the Wellcome Trust=92s =91major contribution=20
in implementing strategies for open access=20
towards the widespread availability of=20
research.  They have shown the way for funding=20
bodies and we hope that others internationally will emulate them.=92

Following the success of the first Award, SPARC=20
Europe has decided to make this an annual event=20
and it is expected that the second Award will be=20
presented at the CERN Workshop on Innovations in=20
Scholarly Communications (OAI5) to be held in Geneva in 2007.

***


About SPARC Europe
SPARC Europe is an alliance of 110 research-led=20
university libraries from 14 European=20
countries.  It is affiliated with SPARC based in=20
Washington, DC, which represents over 200=20
institutions internationally.  SPARC Europe and=20
SPARC work to develop and promote new models of=20
scholarly communication that increase the access=20
to and utility of the research literature.  SPARC=20
Europe is located on the web at=20
<http://www.sparceurope.org/>www.sparceurope.org.=20
SPARC is at <http://www.arl.org/sparc>www.arl.org/sparc.



